3 (2) Louisiana's long-term economic competitiveness depends on a system
4 that is responsive to labor market demand, supported by cross-agency
5 coordination, and grounded in transparent outcome data.
6 (3) Louisiana's students, families, and employers are best served by a
7 Jump Start program grounded in strong governance accountability, rigorous
8 program quality standards, public data reporting, and durable industry
9 alignment mechanisms, and this Act establishes the statutory framework
10 necessary to ensure the program delivers lasting, measurable value across
11 administrations and budget cycles.
12 B. Statement of Purpose.
13 The purposes of this Subpart are to accomplish all of the following:
(1) To establish a coherent, high-quality K–12 career and technical
14
15 education pathway system organized around a clearly defined framework.
16 (2) To strengthen the governance, quality, and accountability of the
17 Jump Start program by creating an independent Louisiana Career and
18 Technical Education Oversight Council with defined composition, authority,
19 and funding; establishing mandatory cross-agency coordination among the
20 Louisiana Department of Education, the Louisiana Workforce Commission, and
21 the Board of Regents; ensuring that approved pathways lead to viable, high-
22 wage, high-demand occupations; and mandating transparent public data
23 reporting.
24 (3) To ensure that every Louisiana student has access to - and can
25 complete - rigorous career and technical education by establishing
26 differentiated provisions, guaranteeing postsecondary articulation credit
27 opportunities for Career Diploma completers, and providing that no student's
28 geographic location shall determine the quality or availability of career and
29 technical education pathways available to that student.
